# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
1. Find maximum Spell power.
2. Create an array `counts` of length `max spell power` filled with zeros.
3. For each potion calculate minimum required spell. If required spell <= maximum spell power, increment counts of required Spell.
4. Update `counts` , so `counts[i] = sum(counts[0]...counts[i])`. So `counts` now contains total number of "good" potions.
5. Fill the results, so `results[i] = counts[spells[i]]`. To save some space, we can use spells as results.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n + m + k)
    spells.size() = n
    potions.size() = m
    max spells power = k

    It can be optimized a little bit. `k` could be `max spells power` - `min spells power`

- Space complexity: O(k)
  We only use additional space for `counts` array. If we consider `results` as additional space, then O(k+n).

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> successfulPairs(vector<int>& spells, vector<int>& potions, long long success) {
        int maxSpell = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<spells.size(); ++i){  //O(n)
            maxSpell = max(maxSpell, spells[i]);
        }
        vector<int> counts(maxSpell+1, 0);

        for(int i=0; i<potions.size(); ++i){ //O(m)
            auto index = (success+potions[i]-1)/potions[i]; //minimum required spell power
            if(index<counts.size()) counts[index]++;
        }

        for(int i=1; i<counts.size(); ++i){ //O(k)
            counts[i] +=counts[i-1];
        }

        vector<int> result(spells.size(), 0);
        for(int i=0; i<spells.size(); ++i){ //O(n)
            result[i] = counts[spells[i]];
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```

