# Intuition
As answer should follow the of spells so we can't change that array.
but if we read question properly then we can see that we only need to count values in potions by which if we product the spells index value which give product atleast success. 

# Approach
As we have to find number of products which will give product with specific index atleast success.
So if we see potion index we can easily see that we if we somehow sort that and find minimum value which gives product atleast success then rest falling ownwards will be greater. so which whill give result easily
Steps
1. sort potion array.
2. traverse spell array.
3. apply binary search to find minimum value giving product >= success.
4. add potion size - index to result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(nlogn)

- Space complexity:
O(n) for result vector

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> successfulPairs(vector<int>& spells, vector<int>& potions, long long success) {
        sort(potions.begin(), potions.end());
        vector<int> result;
        for(auto x: spells)
        {
            int low = 0, high = potions.size() - 1;
            while(low <= high)
            {
                int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
                long long pro = long(potions[mid]) * (long)(x);
                if(pro >= success)
                    high = mid - 1;
                else 
                    low = mid +1;
            }
            result.push_back(potions.size() - low);
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```

