solutions.content:
Loved this problem. First, we need to figure out how to handle prices. 

Since we are going to be using DP array anyway, we can just set the initial price for `[h_i, w_i]` pieces to `price_i`.

Another trick is to do it in 3D, not 4D. For each piece `[i, j]`, we do not need to check all combinations of vertical and horizontal cuts (i * j options). We can just try all horizontal cuts, and all vertical cuts independently (i + j options).

Finally, we only need to try `i / 2` and `j / 2` cuts because of the symmetry, as suggested by [rexue70](https://leetcode.com/rexue70/).

**Java**
```java
public long sellingWood(int m, int n, int[][] prices) {
    long[][] dp = new long[m + 1][n + 1];
    for (var p : prices)
        dp[p[0]][p[1]] = p[2];
    for (int i = 1; i <= m; ++i)
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; ++j) {
            for (int h = 1; h <= i / 2; ++h)
                dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], dp[h][j] + dp[i - h][j]);
            for (int v = 1; v <= j / 2; ++v)
                dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], dp[i][v] + dp[i][j - v]);
        }    
    return dp[m][n];
}
```
