![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/8cb3602b-7564-403e-9d3e-1f4ef5ecd743_1689158545.3771586.png)

```dfs(r, c)``` is max profit of a wood whose size is ```(r, c)```.
First, we can use ```(m+1) * (n+1)``` matrix to store price of a wood whose size is (r, c).
tc of check the price of a wood is O(1). 

enumerating all the ways we can cut a wood,
find the price of two small woods.
tc of enumerating all the ways is r + c.

Total tc is O(m * n (m + n)), sc is O(m* n).
### python

```python
class Solution:
    def sellingWood(self, m: int, n: int, prices: List[List[int]]) -> int:

		# price matrix
        pr_mat = [[0] * (m+1) for _ in range(n+1)]
        for r, c, p in prices:
            pr_mat[r][c] = p

        @cache
        def dfs(r, c):

			# price of current wood
            sub = pr_mat[r][c] 

			# enumerate all ways to cut horizontally
			# size of one of a woods > 0 (r >= 1)
            for i in range(1, r//2 + 1):
                t = dfs(i, c) + dfs(r-i, c)
                if t > sub: sub = t

            # enumerate all ways to cut vertically
			# size of two woods > 0 (c >= 1)
            for j in range(1, c//2 + 1):
                t = dfs(r, j) + dfs(r, c-j)
                if t > sub: sub = t

            return sub

        return dfs(m, n)
```
