solutions.content:
dp[i, j] signifies is the max amount you can earn from cutting an i x j piece of wood.

For every (i, j) pair we cut the piece of wood in the following ways:
1. from height = 1 to i , with width as j
2. from width = 1 to j, with height as i



dp[i, j] = Maximum of:
width cuts: { dp[i][x] + dp[i][x-j] } for all 1 <= x < j
height cuts: { dp[x][j] + dp[i-x][j] } for all 1 <= x < i

Edge cases. It is possible that a single 2x2 might cost less than four 1x1 pieces.
Therefore, you should check each and every piece from 1x1.

The hashmap makes it faster to lookup prices for base cases where each piece of wood can be directly sold as one unit.
```
class Solution {
        public long sellingWood(int m, int n, int[][] prices) {
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> hm = new HashMap<>();
        for(int[] p : prices) {
            hm.put(1000*p[0] + p[1], p[2]);
        }

        long[][] dp = new long[m+1][n+1];

        for(int i = 1; i<= m; i++) {
            for(int j = 1; j<=n; j++) {
                dp[i][j] = hm.get(1000*i + j)==null?0:hm.get(1000*i + j);

                for(int x = 1; x<=i; x++) {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], dp[x][j] + dp[i-x][j]);
                }

                for(int x = 1; x<=j; x++) {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], dp[i][x] + dp[i][j-x]);
                }
            }
        }


        return dp[m][n];

    }
}
```

